{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17606524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17606524"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:12:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:12:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15921"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15921"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.17,0,0.03,0.77]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8612"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63175"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8612"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15921"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48626"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"5442"},{"type":"tags","id":"8724"},{"type":"tags","id":"10623"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20633"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63175"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA pregnant woman at 20 weeks gestation is discussing immunity with her healthcare provider. She is concerned about protecting her baby from infections after birth.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the transfer of maternal antibodies to the developing foetus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immunoglobulin E crosses the placenta from week 16","Immunoglobulin M crosses the placenta from week 20","Immunoglobulin D crosses the placenta from week 8","Immunoglobulin A crosses the placenta throughout pregnancy","Immunoglobulin G crosses the placenta from week 13"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe transfer of maternal antibodies to the foetus is a crucial process that provides passive immunity to the newborn. \u003Cstrong\u003EImmunoglobulin G (IgG)\u003C/strong\u003E is the only antibody class that can cross the placenta, beginning at approximately week 13 of gestation. This occurs through active transport via specific receptors on placental cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other immunoglobulins do not cross the placenta, though i\u003Cstrong\u003Emmunoglobulin A\u003C/strong\u003E is transferred through breast milk after birth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis maternal antibody transfer is essential for protecting the infant from infections during the first 6-12 months of life, while their own immune system develops. Understanding this process is important for timing maternal vaccinations during pregnancy, as vaccines given after week 13 can provide protection to both mother and infant.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Immunoglobulin G crosses the placenta starting at week 13 of gestation via active transport.","Immunoglobulin A is transferred to the infant through breast milk.","Maternal antibodies provide passive immunity to infants for the first 6-12 months of life."],"references":["Palmeira P, Quinello C, Silveira-Lessa AL, Zago CA, Carneiro-Sampaio M. IgG placental transfer in healthy and pathological pregnancies. Clin Dev Immunol. 2012;2012:985646. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3251916/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48626"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15921"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}